{{Belgium-sport-stub}}

'''Cannon shooting''' was contested in the [[1900 Olympic Games]] in [[Paris]].<ref>{{cite web|title= GB Athletics&nbsp;– Olympic Games Medallists&nbsp;– Other Sports&nbsp;– Demonstration & Unofficial Sports |url=http://www.gbrathletics.com/olympic/other.htm#DEMO}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author= John Apostal Lucas |title= The modern Olympic Games |url=https://books.google.co.kr/books?ei=D8VgT4nxBa3LmAXSrZX8Bw&hl=ko&id=w7eBAAAAMAAJ&dq=cannon+shooting+olympic+1900&q=%22cannon+shooting%22#search_anchor|year=1980|page=50}}</ref> It consisted of 17 events, all for men. Only French competitors participated. In later years the [[IOC]] deemed the events of the 1900 Olympics to be either official or unofficial. Cannon shooting was regarded as unofficial.<ref name="Mallon">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=inAwCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA25 | author = Mallon, Bill | year = 1998 | title = The 1900 Olympic Games, Results for All Competitors in All Events, with Commentary | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc. | location = Jefferson, North Carolina |pages=25–26 | isbn = 978-0-7864-4064-1}}</ref> There was no such designation at the time of the Games.

